      "title": "Point wrt ellipse",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Position of a point with respect to an ellipse&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>The point $\\text{P}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},\\,\\,{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ lies outside, on or inside the ellipse $\\frac{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}+\\frac{{{\\text{y}}^{2}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}=1$ according as $\\frac{\\text{x}_{1}^{2}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}+\\frac{\\text{y}_{1}^{2}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}-1\\,&gt;0$, $=$ or &lt; 0.</p><p><strong>Parametric equation of an ellipse</strong></p><p>If we draw a circle with major axis of any ellipse as diameter then this circle is known as a uxiliary circle for that ellipse. Now take any point $\\text{P}$ on the ellipse and draw a line through it parallel to minor axis. The point where this line cuts the auxiliary circle such that $\\text{P}$ and $\\text{Q}$ lies on the same side of the major axis, is known as corresponding point. If the line joining to the center of the ellipse, makes an angle of $\\theta $ with the major axis, $\\theta $ is known as eccentric angle of point $\\text{P}$.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" width=\"254\" height=\"200\">&nbsp;</p><p>If ellipse be $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}+\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=1\\,(a&gt;b)$, then auxiliary circle will be ${{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$ and point $\\text{Q}$ will be $\\left( \\text{a}\\,\\text{cos}\\,\\theta ,\\text{a}\\,\\text{sin}\\,\\theta \\right)$, hence point $\\text{P}$ will be (a $\\text{cos}\\,\\theta ,b\\,\\text{sin}\\,\\theta $ ).</p><p>Here $\\text{x}=\\text{a cos}\\,\\theta ,\\text{y}=\\text{b sin}\\,\\theta $ is called as parametric equation of the ellipse $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}+\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=1$</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd54c03b9dcaf1afea6a"
    }
